body:
This Part contains provisions about the amounts (“the elements”) under—
section 9 (the standard allowance);
section 10 (responsibility for children and young persons);
section 11 (housing costs); and
section 12 (particular needs and circumstances),
of the Act that make up the maximum amount of an award of universal credit, as provided in section 8(2) of the Act.
The elements to be included in an award under section 12 of the Act in respect of particular needs or circumstances are—
... the LCWRA element (see regulations 27 to 28);
the carer element (see regulations 29 and 30); and
the childcare costs element (see regulations 31 to 35).

A person's unearned income is any of their income, including income the person is treated as having by virtue of regulation 74 (notional unearned income), falling within the following descriptions—
retirement pension income (see regulation 67) to which the person is entitled, subject to any adjustment to the amount payable in accordance with regulations under section 73 of the Social Security Administration Act 1992 (overlapping benefits);
any of the following benefits to which the person is entitled, subject to any adjustment to the amount payable in accordance with regulations under section 73 of the Social Security Administration Act 1992 (overlapping benefits)—
jobseeker's allowance,
employment and support allowance,
carer's allowance,
carer support payment but only up to a maximum of the amount a claimant would receive if they had an entitlement to carer’s allowance,
. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
widowed mother's allowance,
widowed parent's allowance,
widow's pension,
maternity allowance, or
industrial injuries benefit, excluding any increase in that benefit under section 104 or 105 of the Contributions and Benefits Act (increases where constant attendance needed and for exceptionally severe disablement);
any benefit, allowance, or other payment which is paid under the law of a country outside the United Kingdom and is analogous to a benefit mentioned in sub-paragraph (b);
payments made towards the maintenance of the person by their spouse, civil partner, former spouse or former civil partner under a court order or an agreement for maintenance;
foreign state retirement pension;
student income (see regulation 68);
a payment made under section 2 of the Employment and Training Act 1973 or section 2 of the Enterprise and New Towns (Scotland) Act 1990 which is a substitute for universal credit or is for a person's living expenses;
a payment made by one of the Sports Councils named in section 23(2) of the National Lottery etc. Act 1993 out of sums allocated to it for distribution where the payment is for the person's living expenses;
a payment received under an insurance policy to insure against—
the risk of losing income due to illness, accident or redundancy, or
. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
income from an annuity (other than retirement pension income), unless disregarded under regulation 75 (compensation for personal injury);
income from a trust, unless disregarded under regulation 75 (compensation for personal injury) or 76 (special schemes for compensation);
income that is treated as the yield from a person's capital by virtue of regulation 72;
capital that is treated as income by virtue of regulation 46(3) or (4);
PPF periodic payments;
income that does not fall within sub-paragraphs (a) to (la) and is taxable under Part 5 of the Income Tax (Trading and Other Income) Act 2005 (miscellaneous income).
In this regulation—
in paragraph (1)(da)
 “foreign state retirement pension” means any pension which is paid under the law of a country outside the United Kingdom and is in the nature of social security;
in paragraph (1)(f) and (g) a person's “living expenses” are the cost of—
food;
ordinary clothing or footwear;
household fuel, rent or other housing costs (including council tax),
for the person, their partner and any child or qualifying young person for whom the person is responsible;
in paragraph (1)(la)
 “PPF periodic payments” has the meaning given in section 17(1) of the State Pension Credit Act 2002 .

The relevant amount is determined by dividing the applicable annual limit by 12.
The applicable annual limit is—
£16,967 for a single claimant resident in Greater London who is not responsible for a child or qualifying young person;
£25,323 for—
joint claimants where either joint claimant is resident in Greater London;
a single claimant resident in Greater London who is responsible for a child or qualifying young person;
£14,753 for a single claimant not resident in Greater London who is not responsible for a child or qualifying young person;
£22,020 for—
joint claimants not resident in Greater London;
a single claimant not resident in Greater London who is responsible for a child or qualifying young person.
For the purposes of section 96 of the Act (benefit cap) and this regulation a claimant is resident in Greater London if—
where the housing costs element is included in the claimant’s award of universal credit—
accommodation in respect of which the claimant meets the occupation condition is in Greater London; or
the claimant is in receipt of housing benefit in respect of a dwelling (which has the meaning given in section 137 of the Contributions and Benefits Act) in Greater London;
where the housing costs element is not included in the claimant’s award of universal credit—
accommodation that the claimant normally occupies as their home is in Greater London; or
where there is no accommodation that the claimant normally occupies as their home, the Jobcentre Plus office to which the Secretary of State has allocated their claim is in Greater London.
